How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly in the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sotchi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have a tendency for the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for citizens of the socialist bloc (also for Czechoslovakians) to travel individually even within the socialist countries.
In case the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example in Poland or in the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter if the individual travel was not allowed.
Travel agencies at this time also offered travel to the West, however, it was necessary to make the queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that, it wasn't earned yet.
The agreement for the currencies that were the condition to travel west was refused to people who were "politically wrong" who could not travel at all.
