It detailed that on Saturday all participants in anthropometric measurements (weight, size, circumference of the size), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (it is sought to identify people associated with child obesity).
Cruz López noted that this investigation is the result of health professionals' concern about the alarming weighting in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was a 77 per cent increase in obesity in boys and in girls of 47 per cent; there was also a dramatic increase in overweight,' said IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers was based on the fact that the population of the country was different from others in its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 per cent of Indo-American heritage, 30 per cent European and 5 per cent African, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
