Another cause is the high caloric input, i.e. the largest consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates of carbon (tamales - meat paste to maize flour wrapped in corn leaves - bread, pizza, burgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM's asphalt would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Chemicals Faculty, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals that the pave were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cases each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who ensured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous pave is adequate, the cassis could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on cassis, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that his laboratory is responsible for developing modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north, to improve performance, and therefore the formation of cassis.
He explained that the asphalt, the heavier part of the oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the spider its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of the asphalt is that at high temperatures, near 180 degrees, it behaves as a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes breaking, it adds.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warns.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México in most of them were covered by a flexible paving consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and later compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, it signals, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well in the paving.
If there was a modified asphalt, these would be better spread, i.e. the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, we put a last layer called the asphalt layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this layer is in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
Being the part of the paving that receives and distributes the effort, the working layer also requires that it has adequate thickness and the material it is made must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, because they significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil wets, the water spreads within the layer it is difficult for it to be so, which is how it melts all layers of the paving and therefore causes cassis.
In the process of training a case, he says, the first to fail is the motion film and only later the asphalt layer is affected, but the damage did not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated to the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the training of caseis and therefore the thickness of each layer of the paving must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent training of caseis.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example bitumen emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow for the repair of cases easily and without having to use high temperatures.
