North Stream, new Russian gas entry door in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, directly linking Western Europe to Russia by crossing the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered into service.
It must provide gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with lightning.
More than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, took part on the Baltic coast last Tuesday between the orchestra and the final buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, the new pipeline that directly connects Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, the German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, turned together the steering wheel of the valve leading the entry of the Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas will arrive every year in Western Europe with a first tube of 1,224 km connecting the Saint Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Poméranie.
A second tube has to be completed at the end of 2012, allowing to deliver a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third on the same path.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge building has victory air.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will be able to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
As far as the debate is concerned, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But it is at the price of a weakening Europe of energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia knew, in five years' time, that it would triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich western countries, heavily gas-consumers, and whose settlements are in decline.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," said François Fillon, inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which major gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles shown by the leaders of Gazprom, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical operation.
The submarine tube is made of concrete steel to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It is based on the bottom of the sea, 200 m on average.
To build it, it had to be avoided from land mines dating from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, with caution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for North Stream.
There was also a need to multiply measures to protect wildlife and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts all its length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned across Sweden, but the project was abandoned by the Swedish authorities while they were reluctant to see a Russian state company permanently set up across their coasts.
"In case of emergency, we stop the gas pass in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builders who planned the sourties to know a escape every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, trained by a ship, for external observation, as well as by a device circulating inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigarette, it is inserted inside the tube, with a diameter of one metre, and it is pushed by the gas.
On arrival, after three complete days of travel at a speed of 3 metres, he provides precise information on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without having to make the least repair.
Gas circulation is simply covered by pressure.
It is 200 bars away, and 100 at arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
There were Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as Dutch Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its seat in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented this company, for 20 renewable years, the total capacity of gas transport.
" Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment rose to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to get back to their expense, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy shoreline planted with pine trees.
Valves, heights of 4.5 meters, form the gas output door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that arrives before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since Tuesday, this terminal has received a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
With full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
